## Executive Summary

Norad is a major humanitarian donor with substantial but highly variable
funding, averaging \$22.4 million annually, marked by large, infrequent
transactions. Its increasing geographic reach—from 6 to 17 countries
between 2022-2025—reflects growing global engagement. Norad prioritizes
broad global initiatives alongside regional programs, with significant
funding concentration in global categories. Compared to peers, it
maintains a conservative earmarking approach (~25%), suggesting
opportunities to advocate for more targeted allocations. Funding
volatility and low transaction frequency pose challenges for steady
project financing, highlighting the need for proposals that align with
Norad’s shifting regional priorities and accommodate its funding rhythms
to optimize impact and partnership potential.

## Funding

The chart displays total funding from the Norwegian Agency for

distribution of funds over time. These dynamics imply that Norad funding
experiences periods of high concentration which may be linked to

this volatility when designing funding requests, ensuring alignment with
periods and regions demonstrating historically higher funding levels.

## Volatility

This visualization presents the funding volatility of Norad, the
Norwegian Agency for Development Cooperation, through 70 transactions
dated between February 2023 and December 2025. Norad’s average
transaction amount is 5.1 million US dollars, significantly larger than
the benchmark average of 2.7 million US dollars among the top 10 other
donors. However, Norad conducts an average of only 23.3 transactions per
year, substantially fewer than the benchmark’s average of 376.8
transactions per year. The scatter points and trend lines illustrate
that Norad’s funding is characterized by relatively few, high-value
transactions, suggesting a funding approach that relies on larger, less
frequent disbursements. This pattern may impact project planning and
cash flow reliability for partners reliant on Norad funding. For
humanitarian proposal writers, it is important to consider the potential
challenges of funding predictability and smoothing costs over time when
engaging with Norad. The relatively lower transaction frequency implies
that proposals or evaluations requiring steady funding streams may need
to incorporate risk mitigation strategies for funding gaps. In summary,
Norad provides substantial funding amounts but with low transaction
frequency, indicating a funding profile that prioritizes larger sums per
transaction over numerous smaller ones.
